04240nam a22006255i 9780691237640DE-B159720211027022714.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||211027t20211989nju    fo  d z      eng d  a97806912376407 a10.1515/97806912376402doi  a(DE-B1597)602092  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anjucUS-NJ 4aB3998 7aPHI0090002bisacsh04a199/.4922231 aYovel, Yirmiyahu, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aSpinoza and Other Heretics, Volume 2 :bThe Adventures of Immanence /cYirmiyahu Yovel. 1aPrinceton, NJ : bPrinceton University Press, c[2021] 4c©1989  a1 online resource (248 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPREFACE -- tNOTE ON SOURCES -- tSpinoza and Other Heretics -- tCHAPTER I. Spinoza and Kant; Critique of Religion and Biblical Hermeneutics -- tCHAPTER 2. Spinoza and Hegel: The Immanent God— Substance or Spirit -- tCHAPTER 3. Spinoza in Heine, Hess, Feuerbach: The Naturalization of Man -- tCHAPTER 4. Spinoza and Marx: Man-in-Nature and the Science of Redemption -- tCHAPTER 5. Spinoza and Nietzsche: Amor dei and Amorfati -- tCHAPTER 6. Spinoza and Freud: Self-Knowledge as Emancipation -- tCHAPTER 7. Epilogue: Immanence and Finitude -- tAFTERWORD -- tNOTES -- tINDEX0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThis ambitious study presents Baruch Spinoza (1632-1677) as the most outstanding and influential thinker of modernity—and examines the question of whether he was the "first secular Jew." A number-one bestseller in Israel, Spinoza and Other Heretics is made up of two volumes—The Marrano of Reason and The Adventures of Immanence. Yirmiyahu Yovel shows how Spinoza grounded a philosophical revolution in a radically new principlethe philosophy of immanence, or the idea that this world is all there is—and how he thereby anticipated secularization, the Enlightenment, the disintegration of ghetto life, and the rise of natural science and the liberal-democratic state.In The Adventures of Immanence, Yovel discloses the presence of Spinoza's philosophical revolution in the work of later thinkers who helped shape the modern mind. He claims it is no accident that some of the most unorthodox and innovative figures in the past two centuries—including Goethe, Kant, Hegel, Heine, Marx, Nietzsche, Freud, and Einstein—were profoundly influenced by Spinoza and shared his view that immanent reality is the only source of valid social and political norms and that recognizing this fact is necessary for human liberation. But what is immanent reality, and how is liberation to be construed? In a work that constitutes a retelling of much of Western intellectual history, Yovel analyzes the rival answers given to these questions and, in so doing, provides a fresh view of a wide range of individual thinkers.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 27. Okt 2021) 0aImmanence (Philosophy)xHistoryy17th century. 0aMarranos. 7aPHILOSOPHY / History & Surveys / General.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978069123764040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780691237640423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780691237640/original  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK